  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Published in 2014 by Peter Lang Verlag, <em>Milit\u00e4r und Gesellschaft in Preu\u00dfen \u2013 Quellen zur Milit\u00e4rsozialisation 1713\u20131806</em> is a specialist archival source volume that has accumulated nearly 2,000 downloads through the OAPEN open-access platform, signalling a steady and active readership within the community of historians and archivists concerned with early modern Prussian military history.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Edited by J\u00fcrgen Kloosterhuis, Bernhard R. Kroener, Klaus Neitmann, and Ralf Pr\u00f6ve \u2014 four scholars whose collective work spans the social, institutional, and military history of Brandenburg-Prussia \u2014 this volume occupies volume 27 of the <em>Quellen, Findb\u00fccher und Inventare des Brandenburgischen Landeshauptarchivs</em> series. That placement situates the book within a long-running archival publication programme dedicated to making primary sources from the Brandenburg State Main Archive accessible to researchers. The chronological scope, from the accession of Frederick William I in 1713 to the collapse of the Frederician military state in 1806, encompasses the era during which the Prussian army became one of the defining institutions of European statecraft.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book's primary contribution is source-based rather than interpretive: it provides researchers with edited and catalogued documentary material bearing on military socialization \u2014 the processes by which individuals were recruited into, disciplined within, and shaped by Prussian military culture across nearly a century. This archival orientation explains the conceptual footprint assigned to the work, which touches on political science, psychology, and philosophy, reflecting the interdisciplinary reach of socialization as an analytical category. The volume thus bridges traditional military history and the newer social and cultural histories of the army that have animated German historiography since the 1990s.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">In terms of measurable reach, the book has been downloaded 1,986 times through OAPEN, with usage distributed across all months of the recorded year rather than concentrated in a single spike \u2014 a pattern more consistent with sustained scholarly utility than with a single promotional moment. The download profile shows its highest activity in January (268 downloads) and April (218 downloads), periods that correspond broadly to the rhythms of academic research and course preparation, suggesting genuine integration into research workflows. The book is also listed on commercial platforms including Amazon and Goodreads, extending its visibility beyond purely institutional channels, and holds physical library holdings in at least four institutions recorded through Open Library.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Formal citation counts remain at zero in indexed databases, a finding that warrants contextual interpretation rather than dismissal. Archival source volumes of this kind serve a use pattern different from monographs or journal articles: researchers consult and draw upon the primary materials they present without necessarily citing the editorial apparatus itself in ways that bibliometric systems capture. The book's percentile ranking reflects this dynamic. Taken together, the evidence points to a publication that fulfils a clear and durable infrastructural role for historians of early modern Prussia \u2014 less visible in citation networks than in the reading rooms, digital archives, and research projects where its documentary content does its most consequential work.</p>",
